        </p>
      </boxed-text>
      <p>With the increase of the number of samples, the training time of BioSeq-Diabolo increases obviously, while its test time is roughly linearly with the number of test samples (see <bold><xref rid="pcbi.1011214.g006" ref-type="fig">Fig 6</xref></bold>). BioSeq-Diabolo achieved an ROC1 of 0.927 trained with 50000 samples for predicting 50000 test samples. The corresponding training time and test time are 3580 seconds and 243 seconds, respectively. For large scale analysis, we suggest the users to use the stand-alone package. And when the number of samples is the same, the time required for different methods to get the result from scratch are show in <bold><xref rid="pcbi.1011214.s007" ref-type="supplementary-material">S2 Fig</xref></bold>. Interaction methods and representation methods (both are based on deep-learning) consume more time than distribution methods (based on traditional machine learning methods).</p>
